    en: "CPLR Article 78 (Sections 7801-7806) is the special proceeding New York uses to challenge government agency decisions, official refusals to act, and administrative determinations. It merged the old common-law writs of mandamus (compel action), prohibition (stop improper jurisdiction), and certiorari (review an administrative record) into one streamlined procedure. An aggrieved party files a verified petition in Supreme Court, serves the respondent agency, and the court reviews on the administrative record. The standard of review depends on the type of challenge: arbitrary-and-capricious for discretionary decisions, substantial-evidence for adjudicatory determinations. Four-month statute of limitations under CPLR 217. No jury; the court decides. Common uses: challenging unemployment denials, Medicaid Fair Hearing outcomes, zoning decisions, professional license discipline, school district actions."
